How can you enforce encryption on all the files uploaded into your example S3 bucket?
Use an encrypted CloudFront distribution in front of your S3 bucket
Use the following S3 bucket policy:
{
"Statement":[
{
"Action": "s3:*",
"Effect":"Deny",
"Principal": "*",
"Resource":"arn:aws:s3:::bucketname/*",
"Condition":{
"Bool":
{ "aws:SecureTransport": true }
}
}
]
}
Using the "Default Encryption" setting in AWS S3
Use the following S3 bucket policy:
{
"Statement":[
{
"Action": "s3:*",
"Effect":"Deny",
"Principal": "*",
"Resource":"arn:aws:s3:::bucketname/*",
"Condition":{
"Bool":
{ "aws:SecureTransport": false }

A developer is tasked with creating necessary configurations for AWS CloudFormation that is extensively used in a project. After declaring the necessary stack policy, the developer realized that the users still do not have access to stack resources. The stack policy created by the developer looks like so:
{
"Statement" : [
{
"Effect" : "Allow",
"Action" : "Update:*",
"Principal": "*",
"Resource" : "*"
},
{
"Effect" : "Deny",
"Action" : "Update:*",
"Principal": "*",
"Resource" : "LogicalResourceId/ProductionDatabase"
}
]
}
Why are the users unable to access the stack resources even after giving access permissions to all?

A CloudOps Engineer is updating Amazon S3 bucket policies for a project. The development team has requested read-only access permissions for all the S3 buckets used in the project.
Which of the following is the correct JSON policy for specifying the necessary permissions?
